# Foundations

This guide covers `Pathogen::*` components, Lookbook previews, and host-app usage. It turns the five Pathogen qualities into practical design decisions.

## Ownership

- **Pathogen** owns shared components, tokens, previews, and interaction patterns.
- **Host apps** own brand mapping and product-specific layout.
- **Previews** show how components behave in product-like work, not a separate documentation style.

Reusable UI should move into Pathogen when more than one surface needs it. Host-local components should still use Pathogen tokens, keyboard behaviour, and accessibility patterns.

## A Good Pathogen Surface

A good Pathogen surface is quiet, precise, accessible, compact, and trustworthy at the same time.

**Quiet** means the surface does not compete with the work. Neutrals hold the room. Accent and status colour appear only when they explain action, selection, focus, navigation, or state.

**Precise** means the parts agree. Type follows role. Spacing follows the 4px rhythm. Corners match the scale of the object. Dividers describe real structure.

**Accessible** means state can be perceived and operated. Focus is visible. Names match visible labels. Contrast, target size, reduced motion, and forced-colours support are design decisions.

**Compact** means dense information remains usable. Smaller controls still need spacing between neighbours. Validation text, focus rings, and row states need room.

**Trustworthy** means the interface feels stable and honest. Clinical workflows should not feel branded for its own sake. Clarity beats polish.

## Building Blocks

Start with the job an element performs, then choose the smallest visual treatment that makes that job clear.

### 1. Intent

Name the job before choosing classes: primary action, cancel, status, navigation, metadata, destructive confirm, selected row, validation error. Intent determines tone, emphasis, colour role, and placement.

### 2. Colour

Use semantic roles (`--pvc-color-*`) in shared components. Palette stops such as `primary-600` and `neutral-200` are implementation details unless no role exists yet.

| Family | Use |
|--------|-----|
| Surface / muted / raised | Canvas, grouped regions, subtle layer changes |
| Border / border-strong | Edges, dividers, table rules, framed controls |
| Text / text-muted | Body copy, labels, hints, secondary information |
| Accent / accent-strong | Links, selected state, brand action, outline emphasis |
| Accent solid / solid-hover | Filled primary action |
| Danger / danger-strong | Error text, destructive outline and ghost actions |
| Danger solid / solid-hover | Confirmed destructive action |
| Success / warning | Status text, borders, icons |
| Focus | Keyboard focus, separate from accent |

Accent and danger have four-step ladders: foreground pair for text and outlines, solid pair for filled buttons. Success and warning are base-only for now. Do not create solid success or warning buttons with raw `emerald-*` or `amber-*`.

Host apps theme accent through `--color-primary-*`. Shared components should not hard-code IRIDA green, Pathogen blue, or any other host brand.

**Current migration state:** `Button`, `CopyableValue`, `Typography`, `Link`, `Tabs`, and `Form` use semantic colour roles. `Tooltip` still mixes semantic roles with `neutral-*` / `primary-*`. Move touched code toward `--pvc-color-*` when the role exists.

### 3. Typography

Sizes are role tokens (`--type-*`) consumed through Tailwind arbitrary-length utilities such as
`text-[length:var(--type-body)]`. Components and these docs share one scale.

| Role | Token | Size | Use |
|------|-------|------|-----|
| Meta | `--type-meta` | 12px | Hints, timestamps, grid footnotes |
| Control | `--type-control` | 14px | Labels, buttons, dense UI, inline code |
| Body | `--type-body` | 16px | Paragraphs, descriptions |
| Callout | `--type-callout` | 18px | Emphasised lead-ins |
| Section | `--type-section` | 20px | Section titles, lead paragraphs |
| Title | `--type-title` | 24px | Sub-page headings |
| Page | `--type-page` | 32px | Page titles via `Heading` |

14px and 16px carry most product work. Larger type should mark real hierarchy, not create display moments.

- Labels for settings and rows: `text-[length:var(--type-control)] font-semibold`.
- Muted copy: `--pvc-color-text-muted` or typography `muted`.
- `Supporting` defaults to control scale for captions and labels. Pass `size: :meta` for timestamps and footnotes; `HeadingGroup` metadata uses meta scale by default.
- Body weight stays normal. Heading weight steps deliberately: `Heading` levels 1–6 map to
  extrabold (page title), bold, then semibold. Levels 4–5 share callout scale; level 6 uses body scale.
  Extrabold is reserved for the single page title.
- Page titles live in `Pathogen::Typography::Heading`; hosts should not override them.
- Set type left-aligned. Following the New Typography, hierarchy comes from size, weight, and
  asymmetric placement — not centring or decorative uppercase. There is no uppercase display label
  component; use `Supporting` for metadata labels.

Prefer `text-[length:var(--type-control)]` in new code. Existing `text-sm` is fine where it matches the role.

#### Migration from pre-token typography

| Removed | Replacement |
|---------|-------------|
| `Pathogen::Typography::Eyebrow` / `pathogen_eyebrow` | `Supporting` with `variant: :muted` and `size: :meta` |
| `HeadingGroup#with_eyebrow` | `with_metadata` or `Supporting` above the heading |
| `responsive:` on typography components | Removed (was a no-op); use role tokens via components |
| `text-base` … `text-5xl` in the Pathogen CSS bundle | `text-[length:var(--type-*)]` or host-app Tailwind scale |

### 4. Spacing

Base unit: **4px**.

| Step | Class | Good for |
|------|-------|----------|
| 4px | `gap-1`, `space-y-1` | Tight groups, icon padding |
| 8px | `gap-2`, `space-y-2` | Control internals, toolbar separation |
| 16px | `gap-4`, `space-y-4` | Forms, fieldsets, ordinary stacks |
| 24px | `gap-6` | Sections |
| 32px | `gap-8` | Major regions |

Line up labels, columns, and action groups to the same rhythm. Avoid custom page spacing unless a shared component absorbs the pattern.

### 5. Radius

| Token | Size | Use |
|-------|------|-----|
| `--pvc-radius-control-sm` | 2px | Checkboxes, tight primitives |
| `--pvc-radius-control` | 4px | Inputs, inline code |
| `--pvc-radius-action` | 6px | Buttons, tabs, grouped controls |
| `--pvc-radius-panel` | 8px | Grids, fieldsets, larger framed surfaces |

Sharper corners suit dense clinical UI. Avoid `rounded-xl` on everyday product surfaces. Pills (`rounded-full`) are for radios, switches, avatars, and true pill controls, not general panels.

<span id="elevation"></span>

### 6. Elevation

| Level | Treatment |
|-------|-----------|
| Base | Border + surface colour, no shadow |
| Grouped | Muted surface or stronger border, still no shadow |
| Overlay | `--pvc-shadow-overlay` for tooltips, popovers, menus |

Use borders and surface steps before shadow. Product UI stays mostly flat; floating layers cast the small shadow because they need to separate from the page.

### 7. Motion

| Token | Duration | Use |
|-------|----------|-----|
| `--pvc-duration-fast` | 120ms | Control colour, border, background |
| `--pvc-duration-default` | 160ms | General feedback |
| `--pvc-duration-overlay` | 200ms | Tooltips, popovers, menus |

Animate colour, border, background, and opacity before position. Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.

## Surfaces

A surface is a bounded work area: a panel, grid, fieldset, dialog body, or preview frame.

Use this recipe unless the workflow needs something else:

- Background: `--pvc-color-surface` or `--pvc-color-surface-muted`
- Border: 1px `--pvc-color-border`
- Radius: `--pvc-radius-panel` for larger frames; `--pvc-radius-control` for fields
- Shadow: only for overlays

`DataGridComponent` is the main framed surface today. Hosts can compose the same recipe from tokens until a shared `Panel` component exists.

## Layout

- Build on a grid before adding emphasis.
- Let dividers show real structure.
- Use asymmetry only when the workflow is asymmetric.
- Leave room for focus rings, validation text, and dense row states.
- Let label, control, help, and action order do the work before adding icons or colour blocks.

Think product utility: GitHub, Linear, and public-sector data tools are closer references than landing pages.

## Buttons

Buttons have two decisions: **tone** and **emphasis**.

| Decision | Values |
|----------|--------|
| `tone` | `neutral`, `primary`, `danger` |
| `emphasis` | `solid`, `outline`, `ghost` |

### Tone And Emphasis

**Primary** moves work forward: `solid` for the main action, `outline` for a secondary brand action, `ghost` for a quiet brand-linked action.

**Neutral** supports the workflow: `outline` for cancel/close, `ghost` for tools and utilities, `solid` only when a strong neutral action is clearer than accent.

**Danger** marks destructive work: `solid` only after confirmation, `outline` when confirmation happens elsewhere, `ghost` for dense destructive utilities.

### Placement

- One `primary` + `solid` per action group.
- Form footers place the main action last; cancel stays secondary.
- Toolbars use `small`, `ghost` or `outline`, and named icon buttons.
- Do not put two primary solid buttons beside each other unless they are genuinely equal choices.

### Hover On Solid Buttons

Solid fills should darken on hover, like pressing further in. Danger uses `red-600` -> `red-700`. Primary uses `primary-700` -> `primary-800` through `--pvc-color-accent-solid-hover`.

### Size And State

| Size | Where | Minimum target |
|------|-------|----------------|
| `medium` | Forms, dialogs, page actions | 44px |
| `small` | Toolbars, grids, dense tables | 24px, with 8px between neighbours |

Use short verb labels. Icon-only buttons need `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, or visible text. Use `disabled` when unfocusable. Use `aria_disabled` when the control must remain focusable so validation feedback can be announced.

Use `Pathogen::Link` for inline navigation. Use button-styled links only inside button groups.

## Links

`Pathogen::Link` is for underlined inline navigation with accent on hover. Toolbar actions should be buttons.

## Toasts

`Pathogen::Toast` confirms background work, sync status, and recoverable errors without blocking the page. Host apps mount a persistent `Pathogen::Toaster` (for example `#flashes`) and stream toasts into it.

- **Placement** — default anchor is `top_center` so confirmations stay in view during dense grid and form work. Hosts may switch to `top_right`, `bottom_center`, or `bottom_right` when chrome (headers, sticky footers, pagination) would collide.
- **Surface** — raised overlay: `--pvc-color-surface-raised`, `--pvc-color-border`, `--pvc-radius-panel`, `--pvc-shadow-overlay`.
- **Status** — pair a semantic icon with the message. Use `--pvc-color-success`, `--pvc-color-warning`, and `--pvc-color-danger` for those types. Keep `info` quiet with `--pvc-color-text-muted` on the icon; reserve accent for real brand actions inside the toast action slot.
- **Type** — message at control scale, semibold; description at control scale, muted. No decorative accent bars or colour blocks beyond the icon.
- **Stack** — collapsed toasts form a quiet deck of full cards: small vertical offset plus a modest scale step (`--pvc-toast-scale-step`) so behind layers read as a stack, not chrome strips. Hover or focus expands the stack to full height. Overflow beyond `max_visible` stays hidden until expand. Prefer `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` → flat list with the same hide/reveal rules.
- **Dismiss** — `Pathogen::Button` `small` + `neutral` + `ghost`, icon-only, with a translated `aria-label`. Errors and actionable toasts stay until dismissed.
- **Motion** — fade opacity on dismiss (`--pvc-duration-default`). Stack expand/collapse animates `transform` (translateY + scale) and height at `--pvc-duration-overlay`; honour `prefers-reduced-motion` in the Stimulus controller.

## Forms

- Native controls first.
- Labels: `text-sm font-semibold`, `--pvc-color-text`.
- Fieldsets: `gap-4`.
- Checkboxes: `--pvc-radius-control-sm`.
- Radios and switches: `rounded-full`.
- Prefer `PathogenFormBuilder` and `Pathogen::Form::*`.

## Data Grid

The data grid is dense by design. It can use `neutral-950` inside the grid frame in dark mode so rows read clearly. That exception does not apply to app backgrounds, sidebars, or preview shells.

Hover, focus, selected, disabled, and active states must remain visually distinct.

<span id="focus-and-keyboard"></span>

## Focus And Keyboard

Focus must show in light, dark, high-contrast, and forced-colours modes. It also needs to remain distinct from accent colour.

**Target pattern:** `focus-visible:outline-2 outline-[var(--pvc-color-focus)] outline-offset-2`

`--pvc-color-focus` resolves to `primary-500` in both modes so focus stays distinct from accent colour.

`Button`, `CopyableValue`, `Link`, `Form`, and `Tabs` use the target pattern.

Do not hide focus with transparent borders. Do not rely on colour alone for state.

<span id="accessibility"></span>

## Accessibility

Pathogen targets **WCAG 2.2 Level AA** for shared components and the host surfaces that use them. Accessibility is not a late audit pass. It is part of how quiet, precise, and trustworthy the product feels.

### How to build

1. **Native HTML first** — use the element that already matches the job (`button`, `a`, `input`, `fieldset`, `table`, `dialog` where supported).
2. **Pathogen components next** — prefer `Pathogen::Button`, `Pathogen::Link`, `Pathogen::Form::*`, `Pathogen::Tabs`, `Pathogen::DataGridComponent`, and related primitives before inventing markup.
3. **ARIA patterns when custom** — if the UI cannot be native, follow the matching pattern in the [ARIA Authoring Practices Guide (APG)](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/) for roles, keyboard behaviour, focus management, and state.

Fix accessibility in Pathogen primitives first. Host apps inherit those gains everywhere the primitive is used.

### Pathogen requirements

- **Semantic HTML** — correct element, label association, and document structure.
- **Contrast** — WCAG AA for text and meaningful UI state (see [What is WCAG?](https://www.wcag.com/resource/what-is-wcag/) for an overview; [WCAG 2.2](https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG22/) for success criteria).
- **Visible focus** — `focus-visible` treatment in light, dark, high-contrast, and forced-colours modes ([Focus and keyboard](#focus-and-keyboard)).
- **Names and labels** — visible labels, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby` where the visible UI does not speak for itself (especially icon-only controls).
- **State beyond colour** — pair colour with text, icons, borders, position, or `aria-*` state so meaning survives without hue.
- **Keyboard** — full operation without a pointer; logical tab order; no keyboard traps except in modal flows that manage escape.
- **Touch targets** — respect documented minimum sizes; keep at least 8px between adjacent `small` toolbar controls.
- **Motion** — honour `prefers-reduced-motion` for non-essential animation.
- **Forced colours** — custom controls remain usable when system high-contrast themes override author styles.

### Where to look by pattern

| UI | Start here |
|----|------------|
| Buttons, links | [Button pattern](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/), Pathogen Button previews |
| Tabs | [Tabs pattern](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/tabs/), `Pathogen::Tabs` |
| Forms, switches, radios | [Checkbox](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/checkbox/), [Radio](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/radio/), [Switch](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/switch/), `Pathogen::Form::*` |
| Tooltips | [Tooltip pattern](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/tooltip/), `Pathogen::Tooltip` |
| Toasts | `Pathogen::Toast` inside `Pathogen::Toaster` — overlay surface, status icon + text, polite/assertive live regions |
| Data grids / tables | [Grid](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/grid/) and [Table](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/table/), `Pathogen::DataGridComponent` |
| Dialogs and disclosures | [Dialog modal](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/dialog-modal/), [Disclosure](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/) |

When Pathogen and APG disagree, match Pathogen tokens and visual language while keeping APG keyboard and naming behaviour — or document a deliberate exception.

### Further reading

- [What is WCAG?](https://www.wcag.com/resource/what-is-wcag/) — plain-language introduction.
- [WCAG 2.2](https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG22/) — official success criteria.
- [ARIA Authoring Practices (APG)](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/) — patterns for custom widgets.
- [WAI tutorials](https://www.w3.org/WAI/tutorials/) — forms, menus, tables, and more.

Previews should show accessibility-relevant states when they matter: focus, disabled, validation, selected, expanded, and error. See [Preview guidelines](<%= page_path("design-system-preview-guidelines") %>).

## Local Exceptions

Sometimes a workflow needs a different pattern. Name the exception, why the workflow needs it, and whether it should become a shared component or token. Undocumented differences become a second design system.
